\sum The myth of Wrisris, the Guardian of the Underworld.
\in A conversation about a mythological character, Wrisris. Half man, half deity.
\in Wrisris lives on top of the volcano, close to the lake.
\in When you want to see one of your relatives who died, walk into the depths of the earth with Wrisris, and he will tell you what happened to them.
\in If it was sorcery, then you may want to take revenge.  Unfortunately, vendetta was exactly what happened to Gaua a few generations ago, which resulted in the massive loss of population. This demographic downturn was the indirect consequence of Wrisris' powers.
\in Wrisris is a supernatural character who can transform himself (wrisris) into anyone. He can also become invisible, and travel to Australia.
\in Some time after the first contact with Westerners, after centuries of a long life, Wrisris suddenly became old, and died.
\in Epilogue: Wrisris (the Guardian of the Underworld) has been replaced with Wendaam — the Guardian of the river of Oblivion…
\nl He symbolises Tradition, and *access to the Ancestors*!  His death means the disappearance of a certain relationship with our ancestors.
\nl See also the frequent pattern whereby Christian missionaries are often said to have brought peace to communities, and halted practices of evil sorcery. (This is only alluded to here.) 
\nl Yet in this conversation, one feels some nostalgia towards the ancient world that we have lost when Wrisris died.
\nl interview/conversation with no narrative structure!  Results in various repetitions, yet I want to remain faithful to the oral nature of the interview, and keep the repetitions in the transcript.
\nl Note also some slight inconsistencies of person reference + time frames. This is due to the clash between two time references: the generic, timeless universe of mythology;  and the linear chronology of History.
\nl Note also the anchoring of mythology in the narrator's personal life: my gg father buried him, etc.
\nt Check recording + write down my questions in the interview...
\gl Mythe
